-- Options Volatility Rises to Eight-Day High as Futures Slide
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-03-19T17:46:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-03-19/options-volatility-rises-to-eight-day-high-as-futures-slide.html
Crude options volatility rose to an
eight-day high as oil futures retreated.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
May, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 18.76 percent at 1:13 p.m. on the  New
York  Mercantile Exchange. It ended at 17.32 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for May delivery declined 78
cents to $93.33 a barrel at 1:14 p.m. on the Nymex, the first
drop in four days.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
May $90 puts, which rose 26 cents to 87 cents a barrel on volume
of 3,582 contracts at 1:17 p.m. June $100 calls were the second-
most active with 1,313 lots. They dropped 15 cents to 61 cents a
barrel.  Puts made up 63 percent of electronic trading volume. In
the previous session yesterday, puts accounted for 58 percent of
the volume.  May $83 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 3,042 contracts changing hands. They
declined 3 cents to 9 cents a barrel. June $100 calls were up 2
cents to 76 cents on 2,497 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $105 calls with
36,334 contracts. Next were June $90 puts at 32,157 and June
$120 calls at 30,107.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
